238
00:19:35.958 --> 00:19:37.875
Come on, Jess!

239
00:19:37.958 --> 00:19:39.083
Come on!

240
00:19:44.125 --> 00:19:46.333
What about sharks?

241
00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:50.708
You ever see any sharks while you're

242
00:19:50.792 --> 00:19:52.958
scuba-ing or whatever?

243
00:19:53.042 --> 00:19:55.708
I've never gone scuba diving
in my whole life.

244
00:19:57.125 --> 00:20:00.625
- You lied in your essay?
- No. I made it up.

245
00:20:00.708 --> 00:20:02.958
It's different from lying.

246
00:20:04.458 --> 00:20:07.667
Those drawings you make,
you seen those things yourself?

247
00:20:08.583 --> 00:20:10.500
No, but...

248
00:20:15.083 --> 00:20:16.625
Hey! Look at that!

249
00:20:17.042 --> 00:20:18.958
- Cool!
- That's been there forever.

250
00:20:19.042 --> 00:20:20.417
I wouldn't trust it.

251
00:20:21.208 --> 00:20:23.042
Come on. Just try it.

252
00:20:25.458 --> 00:20:26.958
OK.

253
00:20:33.542 --> 00:20:35.667
You got it? That's it.

254
00:20:37.292 --> 00:20:38.667
Thanks.

255
00:20:41.458 --> 00:20:44.208
- What are you doing?
- Getting up higher.

256
00:20:46.167 --> 00:20:47.458
OK.

257
00:20:55.708 --> 00:20:58.958
Wow! That was so much fun.
You have to try it. Come on.

258
00:21:20.375 --> 00:21:21.833
OK.

259
00:21:39.458 --> 00:21:41.625
Let your head hang back,
watch the clouds.

260
00:21:41.708 --> 00:21:43.542
Feels like flying.

261
00:22:09.917 --> 00:22:13.958
- We need a place. Just for us.
- Hmm?

262
00:22:14.083 --> 00:22:17.042
Where there's no
Janice Averys or Scott Hoagers.

263
00:22:17.083 --> 00:22:20.917
Yeah, but when we go back to school,
there they are waiting.

264
00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:22.667
Yeah, but...

265
00:22:22.750 --> 00:22:25.917
...someplace better than
just not being at school.

266
00:22:26.625 --> 00:22:29.542
What if there was a magical kingdom
only we knew about?

267
00:22:30.708 --> 00:22:32.375
I don't know. What if?

268
00:22:32.458 --> 00:22:34.708
OK, well...

269
00:22:34.792 --> 00:22:37.458
...what if the only way
we could enter it

270
00:22:37.542 --> 00:22:39.875
is by swinging on this enchanted rope?

271
00:22:39.958 --> 00:22:42.917
- Enchanted rope?
- Yeah.

272
00:22:43.833 --> 00:22:45.458
Come on.

273
00:22:50.667 --> 00:22:52.708
Leslie!

274
00:22:54.083 --> 00:22:55.125
Leslie!

275
00:23:06.042 --> 00:23:07.833
Leslie.

276
00:23:13.042 --> 00:23:15.375
- Come on!
- Wait up.

277
00:23:44.958 --> 00:23:46.500
Ahh!

278
00:23:46.583 --> 00:23:49.125
We shouldn't be in here.
This isn't our land.

279
00:23:49.208 --> 00:23:52.250
- Not so loud. They'll hear you.
- What are you talking about?

280
00:23:59.083 --> 00:24:01.292
Hey! What's that?

281
00:24:03.417 --> 00:24:06.917
Whoa. Jess, look at this. Wow.

282
00:24:09.417 --> 00:24:12.875
Too bad for them.
They got so close.

283
00:24:12.917 --> 00:24:16.083
- What are you talking about?
- To the kingdom.

284
00:24:18.417 --> 00:24:21.042
- What's that?
- What?

285
00:24:21.083 --> 00:24:24.292
That sound. I've heard it before.
Someone's out there.

286
00:24:24.375 --> 00:24:27.333
That's the sound of the prisoners
rattling their chains.

287
00:24:28.167 --> 00:24:30.042
What prisoners?

288
00:24:30.125 --> 00:24:32.583
The prisoners of the Dark Master.

289
00:24:36.500 --> 00:24:39.417
- We should go.
- Wait, Jess, look.

290
00:24:40.750 --> 00:24:42.375
What is it?

291
00:24:46.583 --> 00:24:48.083
Look at this.

292
00:24:55.500 --> 00:24:58.167
Wow. This is amazing.

293
00:25:02.542 --> 00:25:03.708
Wow.

294
00:25:15.500 --> 00:25:16.500
This is it.

295
00:25:32.708 --> 00:25:34.375
Warriors.

296
00:25:36.083 --> 00:25:39.917
- Try dragonflies.
- No. They're warriors.

297
00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:42.375
From the treetop provinces.

298
00:25:43.542 --> 00:25:47.750
- I don't know this game.
- What game? This is for real.

299
00:25:50.125 --> 00:25:53.958
This is the ruins
of a once great fortress

300
00:25:54.042 --> 00:25:56.542
whose people have been imprisoned.

301
00:25:58.625 --> 00:26:01.583
Jess, you and I have been
sent to free them.

302
00:26:03.750 --> 00:26:07.083
Prisoners of the Dark Master, hear me!

303
00:26:07.750 --> 00:26:10.500
We have come to free you.

304
00:26:10.583 --> 00:26:12.208
Do you hear us?

305
00:26:12.292 --> 00:26:14.250
Show me that you hear us!

306
00:26:22.250 --> 00:26:25.708
You got lucky timing. The wind's
been blowing off and on all day.

307
00:26:27.500 --> 00:26:32.250
Can't hear you!

308
00:27:06.917 --> 00:27:10.000
- Go straight home. I'll see you soon.
- OK. See ya!

309
00:28:35.167 --> 00:28:37.917
Hey, don't you think
we should give her a hand?

310
00:28:41.125 --> 00:28:42.750
Uh... She's... She's fine.

311
00:28:43.250 --> 00:28:45.750
Beep, beep, beep, beep.

312
00:28:45.792 --> 00:28:47.458
...forget. There are four of us.

313
00:28:47.542 --> 00:28:48.875
OK.

314
00:28:50.792 --> 00:28:52.792
Remember to bring your bag.

315
00:28:52.875 --> 00:28:55.333
Why would anyone
want to wear that?

316
00:29:00.958 --> 00:29:02.417
Janice!

317
00:29:02.458 --> 00:29:04.083
- You OK?
- What's the problem?

318
00:29:04.167 --> 00:29:06.917
- Jess Aarons tripped me.
- Uh...

319
00:29:07.000 --> 00:29:09.083
On purpose.

320
00:29:09.125 --> 00:29:11.750
OK, Aarons. Hit the road.

321
00:29:12.875 --> 00:29:15.167
- But he didn't do anything.
- Go.

322
00:29:15.250 --> 00:29:18.958
- It was definitely him.
- I know.

323
00:29:34.333 --> 00:29:38.500
- What happened to you?
- Janice is a very talented person.

324
00:29:38.583 --> 00:29:41.417
She can shoot ketchup packets
over four rows of seats.

325
00:29:41.458 --> 00:29:43.250
Jeez.

326
00:29:43.625 --> 00:29:46.750
Can I wash up at your house?
My mom sees this, she'll be all over

327
00:29:46.792 --> 00:29:49.417
the principal and everybody,
and my life will be over.

328
00:29:52.458 --> 00:29:55.542
<i>Why would Dad do this?</i>

329
00:29:55.625 --> 00:29:57.542
- Oh. Hello.
- Oh.

330
00:29:57.625 --> 00:30:00.042
Mom, this is Leslie.

331
00:30:00.125 --> 00:30:01.958
- Hi, Leslie.
- Hi.

332
00:30:02.042 --> 00:30:04.750
- It's nice to meet you.
- Thank you. You too.

333
00:30:05.875 --> 00:30:08.458
So are you and your family
getting settled in OK?

334
00:30:08.542 --> 00:30:11.958
- Yes, ma'am.
- That's nice.

335
00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:14.625
- Come on. See ya later.
- Not too late, OK, honey?

336
00:30:15.458 --> 00:30:20.417
- Weird and weirder.
- Hey. Be glad he's found a friend.

337
00:30:20.458 --> 00:30:24.208
- Where's your dad work?
- At home. Same as my mom.

338
00:30:24.292 --> 00:30:26.375
- They're writers.
- Writers?

339
00:30:26.458 --> 00:30:29.542
- What do they write about?
- Fiction.

340
00:30:29.625 --> 00:30:31.250
That explains you.

341
00:30:32.708 --> 00:30:36.125
- What do you mean?
- Well, you like to make things up.

342
00:30:36.208 --> 00:30:38.708
And that's what your parents
do for a living.

343
00:30:40.083 --> 00:30:42.708
You know a lot about hardware?

344
00:30:42.792 --> 00:30:44.708
No. Why?

345
00:30:44.792 --> 00:30:48.333
Well, your dad works
at a hardware store.

346
00:30:48.417 --> 00:30:50.083
OK.

347
00:30:50.583 --> 00:30:53.292
All I'm saying is that
you are who you are...

348
00:30:53.333 --> 00:30:55.000
...not your parents.

349
00:30:57.500 --> 00:31:01.083
If they work at your house, you must
get to hang out with them a lot.

350
00:31:03.833 --> 00:31:05.625
Not really.

351
00:31:08.083 --> 00:31:09.833
What's that?

352
00:31:09.917 --> 00:31:12.792
- Grenade.
- There're no grenades here.

353
00:31:16.167 --> 00:31:17.333
Come on!

354
00:31:21.000 --> 00:31:24.417
- Squirrels!
- Part squirrel, part Scott Hoager.

355
00:31:24.500 --> 00:31:27.500
- Squogre.
- Squogre!

356
00:31:27.875 --> 00:31:30.417
The sneaky foot soldiers
of the Dark Master.

357
00:31:31.542 --> 00:31:33.792
- They're attacking!
- We need ammo!

358
00:31:41.500 --> 00:31:43.542
This is not good.

359
00:31:45.458 --> 00:31:48.917
- See them? Up there?
- Yeah.

360
00:31:49.000 --> 00:31:53.042
- Do you? Really?
- Yeah.

361
00:32:03.708 --> 00:32:04.958
Les...

362
00:32:06.167 --> 00:32:07.292
Leslie?

363
00:32:09.042 --> 00:32:12.333
Leslie. Leslie!

364
00:32:14.042 --> 00:32:16.625
Come on. You can see
the whole kingdom from up here.

365
00:32:20.167 --> 00:32:23.208
Isn't this cool?
We can do anything here.

366
00:32:32.917 --> 00:32:34.833
Look at it.

367
00:32:34.875 --> 00:32:37.625
It's all ours.

368
00:32:37.667 --> 00:32:41.167
From the mountains to the oceans.

369
00:32:44.083 --> 00:32:46.750
- What am I looking for exactly?
- You'll see.

370
00:32:46.833 --> 00:32:49.792
Just close your eyes...

371
00:32:49.833 --> 00:32:51.625
...but keep your mind wide open.

372
00:33:06.333 --> 00:33:07.542
Wow.

373
00:33:09.292 --> 00:33:11.333
What do we call this place?

374
00:33:14.375 --> 00:33:15.958
Terabithia.

375
00:33:22.667 --> 00:33:27.125
Shh.
Everybody tiptoe. OK, ready?

376
00:33:28.000 --> 00:33:30.375
Happy birthday!

377
00:33:30.458 --> 00:33:37.375
<i># Happy birthday to you</i>

378
00:33:37.458 --> 00:33:41.292
<i># Happy birthday, dear Jess</i>

379
00:33:41.333 --> 00:33:44.292
<i># Happy birthday to you #</i>

380
00:33:44.667 --> 00:33:45.958
Make a wish.

381
00:33:46.792 --> 00:33:48.792
- Yay!
- What'd you wish for?

382
00:33:54.875 --> 00:33:58.333
- This is cheap junk.
- No, it isn't.

383
00:33:58.417 --> 00:34:01.208
- I love it.
- How? It doesn't even work.

384
00:34:01.292 --> 00:34:04.042
I don't think we have
the hang of it yet, Dad.

385
00:34:04.125 --> 00:34:07.167
You know what? Keep the box.
We'll see if we can take it back.

386
00:34:09.167 --> 00:34:11.667
Daddy, there's something
in the greenhouse.

387
00:34:17.542 --> 00:34:20.917
That's the last thing I need,
some animal chewing it's way in here.

388
00:34:21.917 --> 00:34:24.292
What are you going to do
if you catch it?

389
00:34:24.333 --> 00:34:26.667
These vegetables are our livelihood.

390
00:34:26.708 --> 00:34:29.917
Can't afford to share them
with animals that get in here.

391
00:34:30.833 --> 00:34:32.792
- So, you're gonna kill it?
- Have to.

392
00:34:35.375 --> 00:34:39.625
Well, he's not gonna
get in here now, right, Dad?

393
00:34:39.667 --> 00:34:43.375
Hope not. But if he does,
you just let me deal with it.

394
00:34:44.833 --> 00:34:47.083
Is there anything else
I can help you with?

395
00:34:47.167 --> 00:34:50.875
No, why don't you go on and do
your homework, I'll clean this mess up.

396
00:35:02.708 --> 00:35:04.667
Under the seat.

397
00:35:09.625 --> 00:35:11.792
I heard it was
your birthday yesterday.

398
00:35:16.042 --> 00:35:18.958
- Like it?
- Wow.

399
00:35:19.792 --> 00:35:22.292
It must've cost a fortune.

400
00:35:22.833 --> 00:35:25.000
What's it matter what it costs?

401
00:35:25.958 --> 00:35:27.208
I don't know.

402
00:35:27.292 --> 00:35:30.708
Well, I can take it back
and get a cheaper one, if you want.

403
00:35:32.500 --> 00:35:35.458
Thanks... a lot.

404
00:35:36.375 --> 00:35:39.292
<i># Jess and Leslie sitting in a tree...</i>

405
00:35:50.500 --> 00:35:52.500
Look.
The squogre and the vulture.

406
00:35:52.583 --> 00:35:54.292
Hey, here he comes.

407
00:35:54.375 --> 00:35:57.875
And a guy who can stand up to a squogre
is scared of a Hoager?

408
00:36:00.917 --> 00:36:03.000
Ms. Edmunds?

409
00:36:03.083 --> 00:36:05.958
- He speaks.
- Can I help you with those?

410
00:36:06.042 --> 00:36:09.417
You sure can.
And you just made my day.

411
00:36:12.042 --> 00:36:13.458
- Great.
- I'll get that one.

412
00:36:13.542 --> 00:36:14.833
Thank you.

413
00:36:22.000 --> 00:36:25.042
- Hey, guys.
- Oh, hi, boys.

414
00:36:32.208 --> 00:36:34.583
How come you're so good at that?

415
00:36:34.667 --> 00:36:36.833
- Good at what?
- Building stuff.

416
00:36:36.875 --> 00:36:38.417
You're good at it for a girl.

417
00:36:38.500 --> 00:36:41.375
Same way I'm fast... for a girl.

418
00:36:41.458 --> 00:36:44.000
You know what I mean.

419
00:36:44.042 --> 00:36:47.167
You're pretty good at art... for a boy.

420
00:36:47.208 --> 00:36:49.125
OK, OK, truce.

421
00:36:53.250 --> 00:36:55.708
Don't your parents notice
this stuff's missing?

422
00:36:55.833 --> 00:36:58.208
Not when they're in
the middle of writing a book.

423
00:36:58.292 --> 00:37:00.833
What's that?

424
00:37:02.042 --> 00:37:03.208
Show yourselves!

425
00:37:16.833 --> 00:37:19.208
It's a giant troll!

426
00:37:19.250 --> 00:37:21.500
No, it's a giant tree
that almost killed us!

427
00:37:21.542 --> 00:37:24.042
You think that tree
just fell all by itself?

428
00:37:25.292 --> 00:37:26.375
Come on.

429
00:37:26.458 --> 00:37:29.875
When the Dark Master saw
the squogres weren't scaring us away,

430
00:37:29.958 --> 00:37:33.458
- he sent a giant troll.
- How big?

431
00:37:37.958 --> 00:37:39.958
That's how big its feet are.

432
00:37:43.208 --> 00:37:46.375
- You really think so?
- What else could it be?

433
00:37:48.167 --> 00:37:50.000
What should we do?

434
00:37:55.500 --> 00:37:59.333
If we had a troll hunter, we could
track its scent and sneak up on it.

435
00:38:00.125 --> 00:38:02.125
Hey, look at that! Come on!

436
00:38:04.875 --> 00:38:06.375
I think it went that way!

437
00:38:07.333 --> 00:38:10.583
We rule Terabithia,
and nothing crushes us!

438
00:38:15.375 --> 00:38:16.958
I'll race you to the rope.

439
00:38:23.083 --> 00:38:25.542
I love this place!

440
00:38:43.375 --> 00:38:46.125
Go on, get out of here.
And don't come back.

441
00:38:59.917 --> 00:39:01.875
What do you think you're doing?

442
00:39:01.958 --> 00:39:05.917
- I took care of it for you.
- Did you, now? Now, how'd you do that?

443
00:39:06.000 --> 00:39:08.875
I took him into the forest.
He's not coming back, promise.

444
00:39:08.958 --> 00:39:12.333
Did he tell you he's gonna
stay the hell out of the greenhouse?

445
00:39:12.417 --> 00:39:14.875
No, he went out there
and he's not coming...

446
00:39:14.958 --> 00:39:17.208
Jess, you need to understand
something, OK?

447
00:39:17.292 --> 00:39:21.167
This is not one of your cartoons. This
is just a pest that eats up our food,

448
00:39:21.250 --> 00:39:23.375
money we earn and time we don't have.

449
00:39:24.750 --> 00:39:26.667
- OK.
- Get your head out of the clouds

450
00:39:26.750 --> 00:39:27.917
and do as I say.

451
00:39:28.917 --> 00:39:30.708
OK.

452
00:40:00.875 --> 00:40:02.792
Good night, sweetheart.

453
00:40:04.542 --> 00:40:06.125
Sweet dreams.

454
00:40:07.208 --> 00:40:10.583
Lights out, Jess.

455
00:40:10.667 --> 00:40:12.292
Night, Dad.

456
00:40:18.500 --> 00:40:21.250
Are we slaying the giant troll
after school today?

457
00:40:21.333 --> 00:40:24.083
You've got your head
in the clouds, Leslie.

458
00:40:24.167 --> 00:40:27.708
- Huh?
- There is no giant troll, all right?

459
00:40:27.750 --> 00:40:31.583
Well, you better not let
the Terabithians hear you.

460
00:40:31.625 --> 00:40:33.542
They thought you were their king.

461
00:40:47.792 --> 00:40:51.417
Alexandra, my daddy gave me Twinkies!

462
00:40:51.500 --> 00:40:54.750
Neither one squished, 'cause I
didn't put them next to my drink.

463
00:40:54.792 --> 00:40:56.625
I'd shut up about those Twinkies.

464
00:40:56.708 --> 00:40:59.458
You're just mad 'cause I
got some and you didn't.

465
00:40:59.542 --> 00:41:01.792
Whatever. Don't cry to me
when you lose them.

466
00:41:01.875 --> 00:41:03.417
I'll eat them, not lose them.

467
00:41:09.125 --> 00:41:11.958
Jess! Jess!

468
00:41:12.042 --> 00:41:16.083
Janice Avery stole my Twinkies!
Janice Avery stole my Twinkies!

469
00:41:16.167 --> 00:41:20.000
- I told you, keep your mouth shut.
- She's there. What are you gonna do?

470
00:41:20.083 --> 00:41:22.250
And she makes you pay to pee!

471
00:41:23.667 --> 00:41:25.375
It's a dollar, shorty.

472
00:41:25.417 --> 00:41:29.125
But I don't have a dollar.

473
00:41:29.208 --> 00:41:32.750
That's not fair, is it?
Peeing's definitely supposed to be free.

474
00:41:32.833 --> 00:41:34.208
Free to pee!

475
00:41:34.250 --> 00:41:37.458
Free to pee! Free to pee! Free to pee!

476
00:41:40.417 --> 00:41:41.500
Let's go.

477
00:41:53.917 --> 00:41:56.250
I want my Twinkies, Janice Avery.

478
00:41:56.333 --> 00:41:58.250
What Twinkies, Twinkie?

479
00:41:59.583 --> 00:42:02.875
You're supposed to beat her up.
You're my brother!

480
00:42:02.917 --> 00:42:06.042
Do you know what would happen
if I were to pick a fight with her?

481
00:42:06.125 --> 00:42:08.333
You'll get your butt kicked.

482
00:42:08.417 --> 00:42:12.375
No, I'd get kicked out of school for
fighting a girl. What's that prove?

483
00:42:12.458 --> 00:42:15.167
She stole my Twinkies.

484
00:42:16.750 --> 00:42:18.500
Come on.

485
00:42:20.375 --> 00:42:22.208
It's all right, May Belle.

486
00:42:22.292 --> 00:42:26.125
We'll get her back. Won't we, Jess?

487
00:42:30.667 --> 00:42:33.458
<i>Don't let
the Terabithians hear you.</i>

488
00:42:33.542 --> 00:42:35.458
<i>They thought you were their king.</i>

489
00:42:55.625 --> 00:42:57.708
Jess! Jess!

490
00:43:08.167 --> 00:43:11.750
Oh... Hi! Look at you!

491
00:43:11.792 --> 00:43:16.583
That is your very own, certified,
purebred, giant troll hunter.

492
00:43:17.167 --> 00:43:18.625
- He's for me?
- Yeah,

493
00:43:18.667 --> 00:43:21.083
he just took a giant
pee all over my sweatshirt.

494
00:43:21.125 --> 00:43:23.625
Wow, Jess. Thank you.

495
00:43:28.083 --> 00:43:30.167
I name you Prince Terrien,

496
00:43:30.250 --> 00:43:33.125
giant troll hunter extraordinaire.

497
00:43:33.208 --> 00:43:35.167
P.T. For short.

498
00:43:38.750 --> 00:43:40.958
Hey! I think he smells a troll.
Come on.

499
00:43:44.417 --> 00:43:47.083
Oh, no! We've got company!

500
00:43:47.125 --> 00:43:49.333
Dead meat! Dead meat!

501
00:43:50.667 --> 00:43:53.250
- Dead meat! Dead meat!
- Hairy Vultures!

502
00:43:55.250 --> 00:43:56.917
What's that?

503
00:44:02.000 --> 00:44:04.750
It's a giant troll.

504
00:44:08.958 --> 00:44:10.333
Nice feet.

505
00:44:13.042 --> 00:44:14.375
Run!

506
00:44:17.333 --> 00:44:18.792
Oh, my gosh!

507
00:44:25.458 --> 00:44:27.583
I think we lost it.

508
00:44:29.625 --> 00:44:34.250
Leslie...

509
00:44:34.333 --> 00:44:36.917
- What's its weak spot?
- Does it have a weak spot?

510
00:44:37.000 --> 00:44:38.458
I don't know!

511
00:44:40.125 --> 00:44:43.292
Just making it madder!

512
00:44:43.917 --> 00:44:45.625
P.T.!

513
00:44:48.417 --> 00:44:51.000
That's it! That's its weak spot!

514
00:44:51.083 --> 00:44:53.000
It's ticklish!

515
00:44:54.500 --> 00:44:57.250
- Gross!
- Troll toe jam.

516
00:44:58.208 --> 00:45:00.417
Good boy, P.T. Good boy!

517
00:45:00.958 --> 00:45:02.583
Good dog.

518
00:45:08.458 --> 00:45:10.708
What's Janice's weak spot, you think?

519
00:45:12.583 --> 00:45:14.958
Eighth-grade girl...

520
00:45:15.000 --> 00:45:16.792
...probably eighth-grade boys.

521
00:45:16.875 --> 00:45:18.917
Who's she got a crush on?

522
00:45:19.000 --> 00:45:21.625
I don't know. Let's see...

523
00:45:21.708 --> 00:45:25.250
...coolest boy in
eighth grade is probably...

524
00:45:25.292 --> 00:45:26.875
...Willard Hughes.

525
00:45:26.958 --> 00:45:29.417
- That's it.
- What's it?

526
00:45:30.875 --> 00:45:33.750
Write, "Dear Janice... "

527
00:45:33.792 --> 00:45:36.458
- You do it.
- No way.

528
00:45:36.542 --> 00:45:39.083
Boys' handwriting sucks.
No offense.

529
00:45:39.125 --> 00:45:40.333
It's gotta be you.

530
00:45:42.792 --> 00:45:44.458
OK.

531
00:45:44.500 --> 00:45:46.458
"Dear Janice,

532
00:45:46.542 --> 00:45:50.083
<i>you're the most amazing and
beautiful person I've ever known. "</i>

533
00:45:50.167 --> 00:45:53.958
- How do I know which desk is hers?
- It's got dried-up blood and old bones.

534
00:45:58.375 --> 00:46:01.792
<i>"I do not know if you know this
about me, but I need to tell you,</i>

535
00:46:01.875 --> 00:46:05.292
<i>I think you are so cool.</i>

536
00:46:05.333 --> 00:46:09.208
You are the coolest over
all the other girls in our school. "

537
00:46:09.292 --> 00:46:10.792
OK. Write this,

538
00:46:10.875 --> 00:46:14.500
<i>"Let's find out if what
I think we have is real. "</i>

539
00:46:18.375 --> 00:46:20.625
- Oh, Mr. Bailey...
- Huh?

540
00:46:20.667 --> 00:46:24.125
...I was looking for you.
- Me? Why?

541
00:46:24.208 --> 00:46:27.458
I think someone threw up
in the girls' room.

542
00:46:27.500 --> 00:46:29.708
All right, I'll take a look.

543
00:46:35.625 --> 00:46:38.500
"Meet me by the bus
after school today.

544
00:46:38.583 --> 00:46:41.833
We can ride home together
and talk about us. "

545
00:46:43.625 --> 00:46:46.292
<i>Underline and capitalize the "us. "</i>

546
00:46:46.333 --> 00:46:48.500
"All my love, Willard. "

547
00:46:51.708 --> 00:46:54.833
You know, if we get caught,
they're both gonna kill us.

548
00:47:04.667 --> 00:47:07.417
- I got your note.
- What are you talking about?

549
00:47:07.500 --> 00:47:09.083
That was really sweet.

550
00:47:09.167 --> 00:47:11.458
- I'm saving these seats.
- For who?

551
00:47:11.542 --> 00:47:14.292
Willard Hughes is gonna
ride Janice home today.

552
00:47:14.375 --> 00:47:17.125
- What are you talking about?
- Willard and Janice.

553
00:47:17.208 --> 00:47:19.417
They're totally in love.

554
00:47:19.500 --> 00:47:22.750
In your dreams.
Well, you better tell Willard that.

555
00:47:22.833 --> 00:47:25.167
It looks like he's
heading home in his own bus.

556
00:47:34.667 --> 00:47:36.542
Look at Janice!

557
00:47:40.375 --> 00:47:43.125
Hey, Janice, what happened?

558
00:47:43.167 --> 00:47:45.458
Didn't Willard know
he's in love with you?

559
00:47:48.167 --> 00:47:50.792
Where's
your boyfriend, Janice?

560
00:47:58.875 --> 00:48:02.417
- What just happened?
- He just walked away.

561
00:48:09.208 --> 00:48:11.292
- Yes.
- You wanna go?

562
00:48:11.375 --> 00:48:13.333
- Yeah.
- I wanna come.

563
00:48:13.375 --> 00:48:16.958
- You can't.
- It's a free country!

564
00:48:17.042 --> 00:48:20.333
Don't follow us, or I'll tell Alexandra
you still suck your thumb

565
00:48:20.417 --> 00:48:22.333
and sleep with Mr. Blanky.

566
00:48:24.875 --> 00:48:28.833
- So, what do you say?
- They must have finished their book.

567
00:48:28.875 --> 00:48:31.167
- How do you know?
- Hey, Leslie.

568
00:48:31.250 --> 00:48:33.833
- We need your help.
- Come on.

569
00:48:38.500 --> 00:48:41.417
- Hey, Mom.
- Hey, Leslie, come on.

570
00:48:41.500 --> 00:48:43.667
All right, let's go.
We're on a mission.

571
00:48:43.750 --> 00:48:46.083
Hey, this is my friend, Jess.
Can he help?

572
00:48:46.167 --> 00:48:49.125
So, you're the infamous Jess.
Hi, I'm Judy.

573
00:48:49.208 --> 00:48:51.958
Leslie tells me you're good
with a paint brush.

574
00:48:52.000 --> 00:48:53.667
Grab one and get going.

575
00:48:53.750 --> 00:48:56.667
Come on! I am determined
to have this wall finished

576
00:48:56.750 --> 00:49:00.292
so when the late sun hits it,
we can watch it catch fire.

577
00:49:04.542 --> 00:49:08.750
Now, that's one steady hand, Jess.
That's an artist's hand. Am I right?

578
00:49:10.167 --> 00:49:11.708
Yeah.

579
00:49:12.000 --> 00:49:14.333
You know,
the best prize that life offers,

580
00:49:14.375 --> 00:49:17.167
is the chance to work hard
at work worth doing.

581
00:49:17.208 --> 00:49:19.292
Teddy Roosevelt said that, not me.

582
00:49:57.042 --> 00:50:01.000
- Wow.
- What did I tell you? Was it worth it?

583
00:50:29.167 --> 00:50:30.667
Hey, guys.

584
00:50:30.750 --> 00:50:33.250
Jess, get started on your homework, OK?

585
00:50:33.333 --> 00:50:35.958
I'm managing the store
on weekends, starting soon,

586
00:50:36.042 --> 00:50:38.792
I need you to pick up
on some chores around here.

587
00:50:38.875 --> 00:50:41.458
You know, the best prize
that life can offer

588
00:50:41.542 --> 00:50:44.375
is working hard at work worth doing.

589
00:50:59.167 --> 00:51:00.417
Hey...

590
00:51:02.625 --> 00:51:05.042
...have you taken art classes?

591
00:51:05.125 --> 00:51:08.542
No, I...
I just made them up myself.

592
00:51:08.583 --> 00:51:10.375
You're really talented.

593
00:51:13.708 --> 00:51:17.042
Jess, don't let those other kids
get in your way.

594
00:51:19.375 --> 00:51:22.625
- Oh, here you go.
- Thank you.

595
00:51:27.042 --> 00:51:28.958
I just went to use the girl's room.

596
00:51:29.042 --> 00:51:31.333
Someone's in a stall,
crying their eyes out,

597
00:51:31.375 --> 00:51:33.542
and I think it's Janice Avery.

598
00:51:33.625 --> 00:51:35.583
It can't be the trick we played, can it?

599
00:51:35.667 --> 00:51:37.500
No way. But come here.

600
00:51:41.750 --> 00:51:43.583
Free to pee!

601
00:51:43.833 --> 00:51:45.833
Get out of here!

602
00:51:45.875 --> 00:51:49.333
Get out of here, now!

603
00:51:51.250 --> 00:51:54.208
- You should go talk to her.
- You kidding?

604
00:51:54.250 --> 00:51:57.625
It's not "skinned knee crying,"
it's something serious.

605
00:51:57.708 --> 00:52:00.042
It's the girls' bathroom,
I can't go in there.

606
00:52:00.125 --> 00:52:03.167
- I don't wanna go in there alone.
- What's the matter?

607
00:52:03.250 --> 00:52:07.208
A girl who can stand up to a giant troll
is afraid of some dumb eighth grader?

608
00:52:40.542 --> 00:52:41.792
Sorry.

609
00:52:41.875 --> 00:52:45.167
- Go on, tell me.
- No, I don't wanna tell you.

610
00:52:45.208 --> 00:52:47.750
- Why not?
- I'll tell you there.

611
00:52:51.667 --> 00:52:55.625
He, like, came up to me.
I'm pretty sure he likes me.

612
00:53:03.125 --> 00:53:05.750
No way! I like Tony!

613
00:53:09.750 --> 00:53:12.333
Her dad gets really mad at her.

614
00:53:12.375 --> 00:53:16.208
So? My dad gets mad at me...
pretty much all the time.

615
00:53:16.250 --> 00:53:18.542
- He hits her.
- Oh.

616
00:53:18.583 --> 00:53:22.583
Some neighbor heard them
yelling so loud, they called the police.

617
00:53:22.667 --> 00:53:26.792
And it got out. And all the seventh
and the eighth graders know about it.

618
00:53:26.875 --> 00:53:32.042
- Whoa.
- Which explains, like, a lot.

619
00:53:34.042 --> 00:53:37.333
Well, what did you say to her?

620
00:53:37.417 --> 00:53:40.917
Well, I told her about not having a TV

621
00:53:41.000 --> 00:53:42.875
and everyone laughing at me.

622
00:53:42.958 --> 00:53:45.958
I know what it's like
to have everyone think I was weird.

623
00:53:46.042 --> 00:53:48.000
Then what'd she say?

624
00:53:48.083 --> 00:53:50.250
She asked me for advice.

625
00:53:51.417 --> 00:53:53.333
Janice Avery asked you for advice?

626
00:53:53.417 --> 00:53:55.792
- Yeah.
- And?

627
00:53:55.875 --> 00:53:58.250
Well, I told her just to pretend

628
00:53:58.333 --> 00:54:01.458
that she had no idea
what anyone was talking about,

629
00:54:01.542 --> 00:54:06.333
and in a few weeks' time,
everybody would just forget about it.

630
00:54:06.417 --> 00:54:08.292
Man...

631
00:54:08.375 --> 00:54:10.000
Then I gave her a piece of gum.

632
00:54:11.375 --> 00:54:13.417
- We should go.
- Yeah.

633
00:54:14.417 --> 00:54:17.542
- Wanna come back tomorrow?
- Can't. I got chores.

634
00:54:17.625 --> 00:54:20.500
- How about the next day?
- Sunday we go to church.

635
00:54:20.583 --> 00:54:22.625
- Can I come?
- You'd hate it.

636
00:54:22.708 --> 00:54:26.208
- No, I think it'd be cool.
- Uh, girls can't wear pants.

637
00:54:26.292 --> 00:54:30.667
- I've got dresses, Jess.
- You in a dress? That'd be a sight!

638
00:54:31.250 --> 00:54:32.375
See ya!

639
00:55:23.625 --> 00:55:26.708
That's what we need.
Bells... in Terabithia.

640
00:55:31.708 --> 00:55:33.667
I'm really glad I came.

641
00:55:33.750 --> 00:55:36.625
That whole Jesus thing,
it's really interesting.

642
00:55:36.708 --> 00:55:39.083
It's not interesting.
It's scary!

643
00:55:39.125 --> 00:55:41.542
It's nailing holes through your hands.

644
00:55:41.583 --> 00:55:45.292
It's 'cause we're all vile sinners.
God made Jesus die.

645
00:55:45.375 --> 00:55:48.250
- You really think that's true?
- It's in the Bible.

646
00:55:48.750 --> 00:55:50.875
You have to believe it,
and you hate it.

647
00:55:51.500 --> 00:55:54.667
I don't have to believe it,
and I think it's beautiful.

648
00:55:54.750 --> 00:55:57.583
- You gotta believe the Bible, Leslie.
- Why?

649
00:55:57.625 --> 00:56:00.375
'Cause if you
don't believe in the Bible,

650
00:56:00.417 --> 00:56:02.583
God will damn you to hell when you die.

651
00:56:02.667 --> 00:56:04.875
Wow, May Belle.
Where'd you hear that?

652
00:56:04.917 --> 00:56:06.750
That's right, huh, Jess?

653
00:56:06.792 --> 00:56:11.000
God damns you to hell
if you don't believe in the Bible.

654
00:56:11.083 --> 00:56:13.542
- I think so.
- Well, I don't think so.

655
00:56:13.583 --> 00:56:17.417
I seriously do not think God
goes around damning people to hell.

656
00:56:17.500 --> 00:56:20.167
He's too busy running all this.

657
00:56:26.167 --> 00:56:29.083
Hey, Jess.
Give me a hand.

658
00:56:30.375 --> 00:56:32.292
Yeah. I'm coming.

659
00:56:34.250 --> 00:56:36.500
Get my drill out of the greenhouse.

660
00:56:55.083 --> 00:56:57.042
You haven't managed
to kill those yet?

661
00:56:57.125 --> 00:56:58.875
Not funny.

662
00:56:58.917 --> 00:57:00.125
Look.

663
00:57:00.750 --> 00:57:02.917
Ever thought of
putting them in the sun?

664
00:57:17.500 --> 00:57:19.958
Jess. Jess.

665
00:57:20.042 --> 00:57:23.292
- Where are my keys?
- What?

666
00:57:23.375 --> 00:57:26.292
My keys. You never gave them back to me.

667
00:57:34.208 --> 00:57:36.125
- Think!
- I put the drill down here.

668
00:57:36.208 --> 00:57:39.417
Damn it, the keys to the store
are on it, the register, all of it.

669
00:57:39.458 --> 00:57:42.500
They have to replace those locks,
$ 700 out of my paycheck.

670
00:57:42.583 --> 00:57:44.125
They gotta be right here.

671
00:57:44.208 --> 00:57:47.458
- If I don't have those keys...
- I'll find them, Dad. I promise.

672
00:57:47.542 --> 00:57:50.750
Why don't you draw me some money
to pay for it? How about that?

673
00:57:50.833 --> 00:57:53.042
Make yourself useful,
draw me some money.

674
00:57:53.125 --> 00:57:54.542
I said I'll find them.

675
00:57:59.292 --> 00:58:02.917
You look awful.
What's the matter?

676
00:58:03.000 --> 00:58:04.917
I lost the keys where my dad works,

677
00:58:04.958 --> 00:58:07.750
and now he has to get
new keys made, and locks.

678
00:58:07.833 --> 00:58:09.458
May Belle?

679
00:58:09.542 --> 00:58:11.958
Please don't anyone get mad at me.

680
00:58:12.000 --> 00:58:14.375
- What?
- He...

681
00:58:14.458 --> 00:58:17.667
- I know where your dad's keys are.
- You do?

682
00:58:18.333 --> 00:58:21.083
You know the bells
we talked about making?

683
00:58:21.167 --> 00:58:24.500
Well, it was meant to be a surprise.

684
00:58:24.583 --> 00:58:26.500
All that clanking metal and junk.

685
00:58:26.583 --> 00:58:29.250
And... May Belle wanted to help.

686
00:58:29.292 --> 00:58:30.833
And you let her?

687
00:58:32.375 --> 00:58:34.833
Why did you tell me
you found them on the ground?

688
00:58:34.917 --> 00:58:37.458
- They were.
- On the ground in the greenhouse.

689
00:58:37.542 --> 00:58:40.000
What's the matter with you?
Dad wants to kill me.

690
00:58:40.083 --> 00:58:42.667
I was waiting for the right time.

691
00:58:45.167 --> 00:58:47.125
So you know where the keys are?

692
00:58:57.708 --> 00:58:59.000
See ya later.

693
00:59:01.667 --> 00:59:04.917
- Tell Mom I'll be home in a bit.
